Problem 2

Part A

Use the Riboflavin dataset from Homework 1, and apply the fsInf and fixedLassoInf function from the selectiveInference R package to perform inference for forward stepwise regression and LASSO. For the fixedLassoInf function, use \(\lambda.\min\) obtained from the cv.glmnet function from the glmnet R package. Compare and contrast the results from these two methods for inference.

require(selectiveInference)
riboflavin.x = read.csv("riboflavinx.csv")
riboflavin.y = read.csv("riboflaviny.csv")
riboflavin.x = riboflavin.x[-1]
riboflavin.y = riboflavin.y[-1]
y = riboflavin.y[,1]
set.seed(666)
x = as.matrix(riboflavin.x)
y = as.matrix(y)
Forward_Stepwise  = fs(x,y)
output = fsInf(Forward_Stepwise)
output

options(warn = -1)
require(glmnet)
x = scale(x,center=T,scale=T)
lambdas = cv.glmnet(x,y)
sigmas = estimateSigma(x,y,intercept = T,standardize = T)$sigmahat
min_lambda = lambdas$lambda.min
betas = coef(lambdas, x=x, y=y, s = sigmas, exact=TRUE,thresh=1E-20)[-1]
output_fixed = fixedLassoInf(x,y,betas,min_lambda)
output_fixed

Part B

Use UMAP to visualize both the row set and the column set from the Riboflavin design matrix – that is, visualize the patients and also the gene expressions across the patients. Do this for the raw data, and also for the data after standardization of the variables. Compare these embeddings with embeddings from \(t\)-SNE.

UMAP

For row data:

library(ggplot2)
library(umap)
x = as.matrix(riboflavin.x)
set.seed(1230)
embeddings = umap(x)

df <- data.frame(x = embeddings$layout[,1],
                 y = embeddings$layout[,2])

# visualize the gene expressions
p = ggplot(df, aes(x = x, y= y)) + geom_point(color = "lightblue")
p+ggtitle("Umap - Gene Expressions Across the Patients")

X.T = t(x)
set.seed(123)
patients = umap(X.T)
df2 <- data.frame(x = patients$layout[,1],
                 y = patients$layout[,2])

pat_plot = ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y= y)) + geom_point(color = "lightgreen")
pat_plot+ggtitle("Umap Plot for Patients")

For data after Standardlization:

library(umap)
library(ggplot2)
set.seed(666)
embeddings = umap(x)

df <- data.frame(x = embeddings$layout[,1],
                 y = embeddings$layout[,2])

# visualize the gene expressions
gene_plot = ggplot(df, aes(x = x, y= y)) + geom_point(color = "lightblue")
gene_plot+ggtitle("Umap - Gene Expressions Across the Patients")

#  patients visualization
X.T = t(x)
set.seed(123)
patients = umap(X.T)
df2 <- data.frame(x = patients$layout[,1],
                 y = patients$layout[,2])

pat_plot = ggplot(df2, aes(x = x, y= y)) + geom_point(color = "lightgreen")
pat_plot+ggtitle("Umap Plot for Patients")

t-SNE

For row data:

library(Rtsne)
tsne_gene = Rtsne(x, perplexity = 6) 

df3 = data.frame(x = tsne_gene$Y[,1],
                 y = tsne_gene$Y[,2])

ggplot(df3, aes(x, y)) + geom_point(color = "lightgreen") + ggtitle("t-SNE - Gene Expressions Across the Patients")

library(Rtsne)

tsne_patient = Rtsne(t(x), perplexity = 6) 

df3 = data.frame(x = tsne_patient$Y[,1],
                 y = tsne_patient$Y[,2])

ggplot(df3, aes(x, y)) + geom_point(color = "lightgreen") + ggtitle("t-SNE plot - Patients")

For data after Standardlization:

scaled_tx = scale(t(x),center=T,scale=T)
tsne_gene = Rtsne(x, perplexity = 6) 
scaled_x = scale(x,center=T,scale=T)
df3 = data.frame(x = tsne_gene$Y[,1],
                 y = tsne_gene$Y[,2])

ggplot(df3, aes(x, y)) + geom_point(color = "lightblue") + ggtitle("t-SNE - Gene Expressions Across the Patients")

tsne_patient = Rtsne(scaled_tx, perplexity = 6) 

df3 = data.frame(x = tsne_patient$Y[,1],
                 y = tsne_patient$Y[,2])

ggplot(df3, aes(x, y)) + geom_point(color = "lightgreen") + ggtitle("t-SNE plot - Patients")

From the plot we can conclude that the standarlization result seems to be worse than the row data. And in general, umap performed better than t-SNE,
